Explicitly NOT changed
──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
- event_loop: tick_once(ctx = *mut PackageManager) is an intrinsic self-as-callback-context pattern (A2 bucket); the raw-ptr is correct, not a workaround.
- progress / root_progress_node / downloads_node: self-referential BORROW_FIELD pointers into self.progress are intrinsic to Progress's node-tree API; already encapsulated via log_mut()-style accessors.
- PackageInstaller: its 8 sites are index-loops, mem::take, and a ParentRef back-pointer into its own node_modules for PackageInstall — all idiomatic (A1) or intrinsic; separate struct, orthogonal to this refactor.
- Intra-TaskScheduler conflicts (preallocated_network_tasks pool slot vs network_*_batch, 4 sites): stay as per-method fixes — have NetworkTask::schedule take the batch directly (`task.schedule(&mut sched.network_tarball_batch)`) so the pool-slot &mut ends before the batch &mut starts.
- manifests-held-across-&mut-sched (Enqueue.rs:1102,2532): stay as per-method fixes — get_or_put_resolved_package_with_find_result takes `manifest: &PackageManifest` by ref from caller, and itself becomes split-form `(lockfile: &mut Lockfile, sched_minus_manifests…, options: &Options)`.

Best available structural change: group the four transpiler fields into a sub-struct so `transpiler_for_target` no longer borrows `&mut BundleV2` as a whole. This is the ONLY grouping that (a) hits the single accessor responsible for most cross-field launders and (b) does not touch the three container_of-constrained fields (`graph`, `linker`, `drain_defer_task`).

```rust
// src/bundler/bundle_v2.rs
pub struct TranspilerSet<'a> {
    pub main: &'a mut Transpiler<'a>,
    pub client: Option<bun_ptr::ParentRef<Transpiler<'a>>>,
    pub owned_client: Option<Box<Transpiler<'a>>>,
    pub ssr: *mut Transpiler<'a>,
    /// Snapshot of linker.dev_server.is_some() + options.server_components,
    /// captured in BundleV2::init so for_target() needs no sibling-field reads.
    routing: TranspilerRouting,
}

#[derive(Copy, Clone)]
struct TranspilerRouting { server_components: bool, has_dev_server: bool }

impl<'a> TranspilerSet<'a> {
    /// Replaces BundleV2::transpiler_for_target. Borrows only self.transpilers,
    /// leaving self.graph / self.dev_server / self.file_map / self.framework
    /// available to the caller.
    pub fn for_target(&mut self, target: Target) -> &mut Transpiler<'a> { /* body of old method, minus lazy-init */ }

    /// Lazy-init path split out; called explicitly by the one site that needs it.
    pub fn ensure_client(&mut self) -> Result<(), Error> { /* initialize_client_transpiler body */ }

    #[inline] pub fn main(&self) -> &Transpiler<'a> { &*self.main }
    #[inline] pub fn client_ref(&self) -> Option<&Transpiler<'a>> { self.client.as_deref() }
}
impl<'a> core::ops::Deref for TranspilerSet<'a> { type Target = Transpiler<'a>; fn deref(&self)->&Transpiler<'a>{ self.main } }

pub struct BundleV2<'a> {
    pub transpilers: TranspilerSet<'a>,   // <- 4 fields collapsed to 1
    pub framework: Option<bake::Framework>,
    pub graph: Graph<'a>,                 // container_of target — stays a direct field
    pub linker: LinkerContext<'a>,        // container_of target — stays a direct field
    pub drain_defer_task: DeferredBatchTask, // container_of target — stays a direct field
    /* ...remaining 15 fields unchanged... */
}
```

Complementary accessor changes (no struct churn):

1. Inline `path_to_source_index_map` at the 3 conflict sites (`:2135`, `:2440`, `:6457`) as `&mut self.graph.build_graphs[target]` so borrowck sees it as disjoint from `self.graph.ast` / `self.graph.input_files`. The accessor is a one-liner; inlining costs nothing.

2. Move `Graph::drain_deferred_tasks` onto `BundleV2` (`:1999`) — trivial, already flagged in difficulty.json.

3. Make `log_for_resolution_failures` an associated fn: `fn log_for_resolution_failures(dev: Option<&DevServerHandle>, t: &mut Transpiler, path: &[u8], g: bake::Graph) -> &mut Log` (`:2249`).

NOT addressed by any BundleV2 refactor (and shouldn't be):
- `:1132`, `:1265`, `:6457(self_ptr)` — FFI provenance: `*mut c_void` ctx handed to C++ plugin callbacks / ParentRef stored in thread-pool tasks. Required by provenance rules; `keep`.
- `:1892/:1901/:1963/:1968/:2070` and `LinkerContext:560` — `MultiArrayList::slice().split_mut()` SoA column snapshots. These are the idiomatic zero-cost way to get disjoint &mut columns; no struct change helps. Bucket A1 (delete comment).
- `LinkerContext:1060/:2230/:2479/:2499`, `ParseTask:2224/:2731` — conflicts inside LinkerContext / Chunk / Worker / ParseTask, not BundleV2. Per-method fixes already specified in difficulty.json.

Accessor change on the RareData cross-struct API — NOT a VirtualMachine split.

The only field pair that actually conflicts and is fixable structurally is `rare_data` (&mut) vs `event_loop_handle` (&), and the conflict exists only because the RareData socket-group methods take the whole `&VirtualMachine` when they use nothing but `vm.uws_loop()` (a `Copy` `*mut uws::Loop`). `close_all_socket_groups` literally contains `let _ = self;` — its `&mut self` is unused too.

Change `src/jsc/rare_data.rs`:

```rust
impl RareData {
    #[inline]
    fn lazy_group<'a>(g: &'a mut SocketGroup, loop_: *mut uws::Loop) -> &'a mut SocketGroup {
        if g.loop_.is_null() { g.init(loop_, None, core::ptr::null_mut()); }
        g
    }
    pub fn spawn_ipc_group(&mut self, loop_: *mut uws::Loop) -> &mut SocketGroup {
        Self::lazy_group(&mut self.spawn_ipc_group, loop_)
    }
    // same for test_parallel_ipc_group, bun_connect_group<SSL>, postgres_group<SSL>,
    //          mysql_group<SSL>, valkey_group<SSL>, ws_upgrade_group<SSL>, ws_client_group<SSL>

    // Drop both receivers — neither is used.
    pub fn close_all_socket_groups(loop_: *mut uws::Loop) {
        let loop_mut = unsafe { &mut *loop_ };
        let mut rounds: u8 = 0;
        while rounds < 8 { if !loop_mut.close_all_groups() { break; } rounds += 1; }
        loop_mut.drain_closed_sockets();
    }
}
```

Optional convenience on VirtualMachine so callers don't repeat `let loop_ = self.uws_loop(); self.rare_data()...`:

```rust
impl VirtualMachine {
    #[inline]
    pub fn rare_and_loop(&mut self) -> (&mut RareData, *mut uws::Loop) {
        let loop_ = self.uws_loop();               // Copy *mut, borrows &self briefly
        (self.rare_data(), loop_)                  // disjoint: rare_data vs event_loop_handle
    }
}
```

Callers at the 3 audit sites become borrow-safe without any `unsafe`/raw-ptr launder:

```rust
// VirtualMachine.rs:1563 + web_worker.rs:1279
let loop_ = self.uws_loop();
if self.rare_data.is_some() { RareData::close_all_socket_groups(loop_); }

// VirtualMachine.rs:6377
let loop_ = self.uws_loop();
let group: *mut uws::SocketGroup = self.rare_data().spawn_ipc_group(loop_);
```

Rejected alternatives for the remaining VM-related sites:
- View struct `VirtualMachineTickView<'a> { el: &'a mut EventLoop, pending_unref: &'a AtomicI32, global: *mut JSGlobalObject }` for auto_tick/auto_tick_active: does NOT work — `EventLoop::tick_immediate_tasks(&mut self, vm: *mut VirtualMachine)` dispatches JS callbacks that reach `VirtualMachine::get_mut()` and mutate arbitrary fields. No borrow can span the tick; raw-ptr per-field deref is the correct shape (confirmed by difficulty.json: `keep`).
- Field-grouping (e.g. `struct VmHandles { global, jsc_vm, event_loop_handle, main }` nested inside VirtualMachine): would let `global`/`main` be disjoint-borrowed, but sites 2372/3530/4521 already do a zero-cost Copy of those scalars. Churn (100 fields, 38+ `extern "C"` exports, `event_loop: *mut EventLoop` self-pointer offset) for zero codegen win.
- OnceCell for `rare_data` to make `rare_data()` take `&self`: doesn't help — callers still need `&mut RareData` out.

Two-part accessor change + a small disjoint-borrow view struct. No field regrouping of Printer itself.

PART 1 — relax `name_for_symbol` to `&self` (it is already read-only in every variant):
```rust
// src/js_printer/renamer.rs
impl MinifyRenamer {
    // body at 299-321 only reads symbols/slots/top_level_symbol_to_slot
    pub fn name_for_symbol(&self, ref_: Ref) -> &[u8] { /* unchanged body */ }
}
impl<'r,'src> Renamer<'r,'src> {
    pub fn name_for_symbol(&self, ref_: Ref) -> &[u8] {
        match self { NumberRenamer(r) => r.name_for_symbol(ref_),
                     NoOpRenamer(r)  => r.name_for_symbol(ref_),
                     MinifyRenamer(r)=> r.name_for_symbol(ref_) }
    }
}
```
(NoOpRenamer and NumberRenamer already take `&self`.) `ChunkRenamer::name_for_symbol` in src/bundler/Chunk.rs:1603 can optionally relax too; all 8 external callers keep compiling unchanged because `&self` is strictly less restrictive.

PART 2 — a view struct that splits the three fields every module_info block actually needs:
```rust
// src/js_printer/lib.rs
pub(crate) struct MiView<'p, 'a> {
    pub mi:      &'p mut analyze_transpiled_module::ModuleInfo,
    pub renamer: &'p rename::Renamer<'a, 'a>,
    pub bump:    &'a bun_alloc::Arena,
}
impl<'p,'a> MiView<'p,'a> {
    #[inline]
    pub fn name_for_symbol(&self, r: Ref) -> &'a [u8] {
        // single centralised 'a launder (arena/source-backed; same invariant
        // Printer::name_for_symbol already relies on)
        let p = core::ptr::from_ref::<[u8]>(self.renamer.name_for_symbol(r));
        unsafe { &*p }
    }
}

impl<...> Printer<...> {
    #[inline]
    fn mi_view(&mut self) -> Option<MiView<'_, 'a>> {
        if !Self::MAY_HAVE_MODULE_INFO { return None; }
        let mi = self.module_info.as_deref_mut()?;          // borrows only self.module_info
        Some(MiView { mi, renamer: &self.renamer, bump: self.bump }) // disjoint fields
    }
}
```
Call-site shape (replaces the re-borrow dance at 1833/4752/4908/5488/6007):
```rust
if let Some(mut v) = self.mi_view() {
    for item in slice_of(s.items) {
        let name = v.name_for_symbol(item.name.ref_);
        let id   = v.mi.str(name);
        v.mi.add_var(id, VarKind::Declared);
    }
}
```
No repeated `module_info().expect(...)` per iteration, no ordering constraints.

PART 3 — site 3069: drop `BackRef<[u8]>` entirely. `options.commonjs_named_exports: Option<&'a CommonJSNamedExports>` is `Copy`; copying it to a local yields `&'a` keys detached from `self`:
```rust
let exports: &'a CommonJSNamedExports = self.options.commonjs_named_exports.unwrap();
let key: &'a [u8] = &exports.keys()[idx][..];   // already 'a-bound, no BackRef needed
```

NOT PROPOSED: a full `PrinterInputs`/`PrinterState` split to fix sites 3942/5288/5359. Those hold `&Symbol` (living in `renamer.symbols`'s owned Vec<Symbol>) across `print_*()` which mutates writer+indent+source_map_builder+prev_*. Eliminating that structurally means re-plumbing ~162 `&mut self` print methods to take `(&PrinterInputs, &mut PrinterState)` — an 8k-line rewrite for 3 neutral sites whose `BackRef` is sound (symbol table is never resized during printing). Instead, centralise those 3 into one documented accessor:
```rust
#[inline]
fn symbol_ref(&self, r: Ref) -> Option<BackRef<'a, Symbol>> {
    self.renamer.symbols().get_const(r).map(BackRef::new)
}
```
This keeps the raw-ptr launder but in one place with one SAFETY comment.

NO STRUCTURAL REFACTOR. The struct is already fully interior-mutable (every field is Cell/JsCell/RefCell; every method takes &self — see comment at src/runtime/api/bun/h2_frame_parser.rs:1181-1184, the "R-2 host-fn re-entrancy" model). There is no `&mut self` at all, so there are no disjoint-field borrows for a view struct or field-grouping to separate.

All 6 audited sites are JS-REENTRANCY hazards, not static borrowck field conflicts:
  - 5 sites hold `&mut Stream` (a heap-boxed value whose *mut is stored in `self.streams: JsCell<HashMap<u32, *mut Stream>>`) across calls that dispatch JS (send_go_away → dispatch, adjust_window_size → send_go_away, decode_header_block → onStreamHeaders). That JS can re-enter `read()` and insert/remove in `self.streams`. No static borrow can span that; the runtime `dispatch_depth` guard + `pending_engine_stream_closes` deferred-free is the designed dynamic invariant. difficulty.json already tags these `fixable:false / keep`.
  - 1 site (2288) iterates `self.streams` then calls `send_window_update → self.write`, which can re-enter JS and mutate the map; the two-phase collect is REQUIRED for correctness (difficulty.json correctness_note).

The only improvement is to centralise the open-coded unsafe deref into the helper that already exists:

```rust
// already defined at h2_frame_parser.rs:2700 — reuse it in the 5 handlers
fn enter_stream_dispatch(&self, stream_ptr: *mut Stream) -> GuardedStream<'_> {
    let _dispatch = self.enter_dispatch();        // arms dispatch_depth → defers stream frees
    GuardedStream { stream: unsafe { &mut *stream_ptr }, _dispatch }
}

// in each of the 5 handlers, replace
//     let mut stream = unsafe { &mut *stream_ptr };
// with
//     let mut stream = self.enter_stream_dispatch(stream_ptr);
// (and at h2_frame_parser.rs:4038 write `Some(&mut *stream)` to reborrow instead
//  of the second unsafe re-deref at :4040)

// line 2288: keep two-phase; swap Vec → SmallVec (already queued in bucket-B2)
let mut updates: smallvec::SmallVec<[(u32, u64); 8]> = smallvec::SmallVec::new();
```

A hypothetical view struct would look like:
```rust
struct FrameHandlerView<'a> { parser: &'a H2FrameParser, stream: GuardedStream<'a> }
```
…but `parser` is already `&self` with full interior mutability, so this is just `(&self, GuardedStream)` with extra ceremony — it removes zero unsafe and adds no checking. Splitting `streams` into a sub-struct likewise cannot help: the re-entrant JS path legitimately needs write access to the same map the handler is reading from.

Additional reason not to invest: h2_frame_parser.rs:1309-1312 — "The fields above are the legacy frame state being retired; read()/host functions will route through `engine` instead." The 5 handlers and line 2288 are all in the legacy decode path being replaced by `src/runtime/api/bun/h2/connection.rs`.
